Sharding is a database scaling technique where you split a large dataset
into multiple smaller, independent partitions (shards) that can be stored
on different machines. Each shard holds just a slice of the data (often
based on a key range or hash), so workloads get spread out: queries hit only
the shard(s) that contain the relevant records.
